{"title_page": "InterAcademy Partnership", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThe '''InterAcademy Partnership''' ('''IAP''') is a global network consisting of over 140 [[national academy|national]] and regional member [[Academy of sciences|academies of science]], [[National Academy of Engineering (disambiguation)|engineering]], and [[Academy of Medicine|medicine]]{{disambiguation needed|date=March 2020}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.interacademies.net/Academies/ByCountry.aspx |title=Membership by country |publisher=IAP |accessdate=1 January 2010 }}</ref> It was founded in 1993 as the '''InterAcademy Panel''' ('''IAP'''). In 2000, the IAP founded the ''InterAcademy Council'' (IAC) and the ''InterAcademy Medical Panel'' (IAMP). The partnership was established in 2016 when it merged the three inter-related networks into IAP for Health (formerly ''IAMP''),<ref>[http://www.interacademies.org/31840/About About: The InterAcademy Partnership]</ref> IAP for Science (formerly IAP), and IAP for Policy (formerly IAC).\n\nThe mission of IAP is for the world's merit-based academies to play a vital role in ensuring that science serves society inclusively and equitably and underpins global sustainable development by advising the public on the [[Science|scientific]] aspects of critical [[global issue]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.interacademies.org/55947/InterAcademy-Partnership-Strategic-Plan-20192021|title=IAP Strategic Plan 2019|date=2019|website=InterAcademy Partnership|url-status=live|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> It has released official statements on socially important topics, including the [[Sustainable Development Goals|2015 United Nations Sustainable Development Goals]], [[Food security|food and nutrition security]], [[science education]], [[biosecurity]], [[Water scarcity|water]], [[science communication]], [[women in science]], human [[population growth]], [[global warming]], [[human cloning|human reproductive cloning]], and [[evolution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interacademies.net/CMS/About.aspx|title=About IAP|publisher=InterAcademy Panel|accessdate=2008-05-11}}</ref> IAP has also advanced [[science diplomacy]] by bringing regional networks together to address global problems.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hassan|first1=Mohamed|date=10 March 2015|title=Academies of Science as Key Instruments of Science Diplomacy|url=http://www.sciencediplomacy.org/perspective/2015/academies-science-key-instruments-science-diplomacy|journal=[[Science & Diplomacy]]|volume=4|issue=1}}</ref>\n\n== Governance ==\nThe highest decisive body of IAP is the [[General assembly|General Assembly]], which meets every third year, and where each member organization has one vote on organizational decisions. At these meetings, member academies elect new leadership, approve new members, report on organizational activities over the last triennial period, and approve a [[Strategic planning|strategic plan]] for the next three years.\n\nIn between the meetings, the work is directed by three executive committees, one for each pillar of the Partnership (or in the case of IAP Policy, a board), supported by a [[Secretariat (administrative office)|secretariat]] from a host academy. Each executive committee/board convenes annually, with two [[Chairperson|co-chairs]] presiding. One of the co-chairs shall be nominated by an academy in a [[Developing country|low or middle income country (LMIC)]]; the other shall be nominated by a [[Developed country|high income country (HIC)]]. Similar rules of diversity in economic development hold for the executive committee member academies in order to represent a global view.<ref>{{cite news|last=Alberts|first=Bruce|url=http://news.scotsman.com/scitech/Independent-research-needs-to-be.3975352.jp|title=Independent research needs to be shared to benefit all of us|date=2008-04-12|work=[[The Scotsman]]|accessdate=2008-05-11|publisher=[[Johnston Press]]}}</ref> The number of member academies composing the executive committee varies: 11 member academies in IAP for Science, 9 member academies in IAP for Health, and 15 member academies in IAP for Policy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.interacademies.org/38723/Governance|title=IAP Governance|url-status=live|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nA Steering Committee composed of the six executive committee/board co-chairs guides the InterAcademy Partnership. From these six Steering Committee members, two are selected to act as co-Presidents. The current co-Presidents are Volker ter Meulen (Germany) and Depei Liu (China). A Board includes the Steering Committee along with one representative from each of four regional networks of academies: in [[African Academy of Sciences|Africa]], the [[InterAmerican Network of Academies of Sciences|Americas]], the Asia/Pacific region, and Europe, for a total of ten representatives.\n\n== Current and former co-chairs ==\n*[[Cherry A. Murray]], US. IAP-Science, 2019\u2013present\n*Masresha Fetene, Ethiopia. IAP-Policy, 2019\u2013present\n*[[Margaret Hamburg]], US. IAP-Health, 2016\u2013present\n*[[Krishna Lal Chadha|Krishan Lal]], India. IAP-Science, 2016\u2013present\n*Liu Depei, China. IAP-Health, 2016\u2013present\n*[[Richard Catlow]], UK. IAP-Policy, 2016\u2013present\n*Volker ter Meulen, Germany. IAP-Science, 2013\u20132019\n*[[Detlev Ganten]], Germany. IAP-Health, 2013\u20132019\n*[[Daya Reddy]], South Africa. IAP-Policy, 2012\u20132019\n*[[Mohamed H.A. Hassan|Mohammed H.A. Hassan]], Sudan. IAP-Science, 2010\u20132016\n*Lai Meng Loi, Malaysia. IAP-Health, 2010\u20132016\n*[[Jo Ivey Boufford]], US. IAP-Health, 2010\u20132013\n*[[Robbert Dijkgraaf]], Netherlands. IAP-Policy, 2008\u20132016\n*[[Lu Yongxiang (engineer)|Lu Yongxiang]], China. IAP-Policy, 2008\u20132012\n*[[Howard Alper]], Canada. IAP-Science, 2007\u20132013\n*Anthony Mbewu, South Africa. IAP-Health, 2007\u20132010\n*[[Chen Zhu]], China. IAP-Science, 2003\u20132010\n*Guy de Th\u00e9, France. IAP-Health, 2000\u20132010\n*[[Bruce Alberts]], US. IAP-Policy, 2000\u20132008\n*[[Goverdhan Mehta]], India. IAP-Policy, 2000\u20132008\n*[[Yves Qu\u00e9r\u00e9]], France. IAP-Science, 2000\u20132007\n*David Challoner, US. IAP-Health, 2000\u20132006\n*[[Eduardo Krieger]], Brazil. IAP-Science, until 2003\n\n== IAP reports ==\nIAP publishes reports and recommendations that utilize the expertise of member academies to address issues of interest to the global [[Scientific community|scientific]] and policy communities. IAP reports are not endorsed by academy members, but instead must have the [[Consensus decision-making|consensus]] of an expert committee and undergo a rigorous [[Scholarly peer review|peer review]] process. Examples of IAP reports include:\n\n# [https://www.interacademies.org/56874/SEM_for_Africa Harnessing science, engineering, and medicine (SEM) to address Africa's challenges: The role of African national academies], 2019\n# [https://www.interacademies.org/50429/SDGs_Report Improving scientific input to global policymaking with a focus on the UN Sustainable Development Goals], 2019\n# [https://www.interacademies.org/48898/Opportunities-for-future-research-and-innovation-on-food-and-nutrition-security-and-agriculture-The-InterAcademy-Partnerships-global-perspective Opportunities for future research and innovation on food and nutrition security and agriculture: The InterAcademy Partnership's global perspective], 2018\n# [https://www.interacademies.org/33367/Enhancing-the-Capacity-of-African-Science-Academies Enhancing the capacity of African science academies], 2015\n# [https://www.interacademies.org/33362/Responsible-Conduct-in-the-Global-Research-Enterprise Responsible conduct in the global research enterprise], 2012\n# [https://www.interacademies.org/33348/Lighting-the-Way-Toward-a-Sustainable-Energy-Future Lighting the way: Toward a sustainable energy future], 2007\n# [https://www.interacademies.org/33366/Realizing-the-Promise-and-Potential-of-African-Agriculture Realizing the promise and potential of African agriculture], 2004\n\n== IAP statements ==\nIAP also promotes its goals through \"statements on issues of fundamental importance to humanity.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.interacademies.org/10878/Statements|title=Statements|website=InterAcademy Partnership|url-status=live|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> Statements present the combined [[Consensus decision-making|consensus]] of the world's academies to provide independent, [[Evidence-based practice|evidence-based]] advice and recommendations to policymakers in governments, international organizations, or academies themselves. Often an IAP statement can be used to [[Globalization|globalise]] an issue on which a [[national academy]] or regional network of academies has already done a significant amount of work.\n\nAn IAP statement is developed following a specific procedure and released only when the [[majority]] of IAP member academies have endorsed its contents. [https://web.archive.org/web/20090124224136/http://interacademies.net/Object.File/Master/8/487/IAP%20StatementsPRINT-1.pdf], p.&nbsp;4. Thus, the statements are intended to represent the consensus of the [[scientific community]] rather than statements of IAP as an organisation in itself.\n\nAs of 2020, IAP has issued twenty-one statements, as listed below.\n\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/53599/IAP-Health-A-call-for-action-to-declare-trauma-as-a-disease IAP call for action to declare trauma as a disease], 2019. Signed by 46 of IAP for Health's 78 member academies.\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/45731/IAP-for-Health-A-call-for-action-to-tackle-the-growing-burden-of-dementia IAP call for action to tackle the growing burden of dementia], 2018. Signed by 53 of IAP for Health's 78 member academies.\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/38806/IAP-Statement-on-Climate-Change-and-Education IAP statement on climate change and education], 2017. Signed by the majority of IAP for Science's 113 member academies.\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/36499/IAP-Statement-on-Science-and-Technology-for-Disaster-Risk-Reduction IAP statement on science and technology for disaster risk reduction], 2017. Signed by the majority of IAP for Science's 113 member academies.\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/39535/Improving-the-reproducibility-of-biomedical-research-a-call-for-action IAP call for action to improve the reproducibility of biomedical research], 2016. Signed by 46 members.\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/48835/IAP-for-Health-statement-Call-for-Action-to-Strengthen-Health-Research-Capacity-in-Low-and-Middle-Income-Countries IAMP call for action to strengthen health research capacity], 2013. Signed by 42 members.\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/19191/IAP-Statement-on-Population-and-Consumption IAP statement on population and consumption], 2012. Signed by 105 members.\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/14745/IAMP-Statement-on-the-Health-CoBenefits-of-Policies-to-Tackle-Climate-Change IAMP statement on the health co-benefits of policies to tackle climate change], 2010. Signed by 43 members.\n#[http://www.interacademies.net/10878/13954.aspx IAP statement on tropical forests and climate change], 2009. Signed by 54 members.\n#[http://www.interacademies.net/File.aspx?id=9075 IAP statement on ocean acidification], 2009. Signed by 70 members. The academies state that [[Ocean acidification|ocean water acidity has risen]] due to increased [[carbon dioxide]] (CO<sub>2</sub>) caused by human activities, and that it probably will rise further with severe effects on [[marine ecosystem]]s if the emission of CO<sub>2</sub> does not decrease considerably. They urge the issue be recognized among the problems addressed by the [[United Nations Climate Change Conference 2009]] in [[Copenhagen]].\n#IAP statement on the teaching of [[evolution]], 2006. [https://www.interacademies.org/13901/IAP-Statement-on-the-Teaching-of-Evolution Signed by 70 members].\n#IAP statement on [[biosecurity]], 2005, [https://www.interacademies.org/13912/IAP-Statement-on-Biosecurity signed by 71 members].\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/13916/IAP-Statement-on-Access-to-Scientific-Information IAP statement on access to scientific information], 2003, signed by 68 members.\n#IAP statement on science and the [[Media (communication)|media]], 2003, [https://www.interacademies.org/13921/IAP-Statement-on-Science-and-the-Media signed by 68 members].\n#IAP statement on scientific [[capacity building]], 2003, [https://www.interacademies.org/13925/IAP-Statement-on-Scientific-Capacity-Building signed by 68 members].\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/13923/IAP-Statement-on-Science-Education IAP statement on science education of children], 2003, signed by 68 members.\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/13928/IAP-Statement-on-Mother-and-Child-Health IAP statement on health of mother and child in developing countries], 2003, signed by 67 members.\n#IAP statement on [[human cloning]], 2003, [https://www.interacademies.org/13930/IAP-Statement-Calling-for-a-Ban-on-Human-Reproductive-Cloning signed by 67 members]. The academies support \"a worldwide ban on the reproductive cloning of human beings\", but at the same time call for \"cloning to obtain [[embryonic stem cells]] for both research and therapeutic purposes to be excluded from this ban\".\n#IAP statement on transition to [[sustainability]], 2000, [https://www.interacademies.org/13933/IAP-Statement-on-Transition-to-Sustainability signed by 63 members].\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/13937/IAP-Statement-on-Urban-Development IAP statement on science and technology and the future of cities], 1996, signed by 71 members. The academies note that there is an ongoing rapid worldwide [[urbanisation|urbanization]]. They state that this in itself is not necessarily a bad development, but that it may have rather negative effects, if appropriate measures are not taken in order to ensure the new city dwellers e.g. access to water and adequate housing. Therefore, active city planning is necessary, and so is further research on urbanization.\n#[[IAP statement on population growth]], proposed 1993, ratified 1994, [https://www.interacademies.org/13940/IAP-Statement-on-Population-Growth signed by 58 members]. The academies state that \"the world is undergoing an unprecedented population expansion\", and that it is necessary to stop it. They noted that the amount of food produced (both on land and sea) per person was decreasing, and stated that many [[environmental problems]] were aggravated by the [[population expansion]]. The academies state that we must reach \"zero population growth within the lifetime of our children\". They enumerate means which should be taken to achieve this, and also to counteract the effects of the population growth on environment and food production, inter alia. This includes furthering equal opportunities for women, easy access to cheap and safe [[contraceptives]], broad primary health care, governmental policies recognizing longer-term environmental responsibilities, and increased research on cultural, religious, and other factors, which \"affect reproductive behavior\".\n\n=== Role in reviewing the IPCC process ===\n{{further|Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change#InterAcademy Council review}}\n\nIn 2010, the council board recommended changes in the [[IPCC]], such as having an executive committee with \"individuals from outside the IPCC or even outside the [[climate science]] community.\"<ref>[http://reviewipcc.interacademycouncil.net/ReportNewsRelease.html InterAcademy Council Report Recommends Fundamental Reform of IPCC Management Structure]</ref>\nMajor changes from then within the IPCC approach include a stronger focus on the treatment of uncertainty (since the IAC 2010 IPCC review) and the involvement of risk management deliberations (based on fundamental conclusions in the AR4 Synthesis Report).<ref name=ess>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1007/s10584-011-0176-8|title = Evaluation, characterization, and communication of uncertainty by the intergovernmental panel on climate change\u2014an introductory essay|journal = Climatic Change|volume = 108|issue = 4|pages = 629\u2013639|year = 2011|last1 = Yohe|first1 = Gary|last2 = Oppenheimer|first2 = Michael|doi-access = free}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[International Council for Science]]\n*[[InterAmerican Network of Academies of Sciences]]\n*[[Network of African Science Academies]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.interacademies.org/ InterAcademy Partnership]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Interacademy Panel on International Issues}}\n[[Category:InterAcademy Panel]]\n[[Category:International science academies cooperation organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThe '''InterAcademy Partnership''' ('''IAP''') is a global network consisting of over 140 [[national academy|national]] and regional member [[Academy of sciences|academies of science]], [[National Academy of Engineering (disambiguation)|engineering]], and [[Academy of Medicine|medicine]]{{disambiguation needed|date=March 2020}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.interacademies.net/Academies/ByCountry.aspx |title=Membership by country |publisher=IAP |accessdate=1 January 2010 }}</ref> It was founded in 1993 as the '''InterAcademy Panel''' ('''IAP'''). In 2000, the IAP founded the ''InterAcademy Council'' (IAC) and the ''InterAcademy Medical Panel'' (IAMP). The partnership was established in 2016 when it merged the three inter-related networks into IAP for Health (formerly ''IAMP''),<ref>[http://www.interacademies.org/31840/About About: The InterAcademy Partnership]</ref> IAP for Science (formerly IAP), and IAP for Policy (formerly IAC).\n\nThe mission of IAP is for the world's merit-based academies to play a vital role in ensuring that science serves society inclusively and equitably and underpins global sustainable development by advising the public on the [[Science|scientific]] aspects of critical [[global issue]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.interacademies.org/55947/InterAcademy-Partnership-Strategic-Plan-20192021|title=IAP Strategic Plan 2019|date=2019|website=InterAcademy Partnership|url-status=live|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> It has released official statements on socially important topics, including the [[Sustainable Development Goals|2015 United Nations Sustainable Development Goals]], [[Food security|food and nutrition security]], [[science education]], [[biosecurity]], [[Water scarcity|water]], [[science communication]], [[women in science]], human [[population growth]], [[global warming]], [[human cloning|human reproductive cloning]], and [[evolution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interacademies.net/CMS/About.aspx|title=About IAP|publisher=InterAcademy Panel|accessdate=2008-05-11}}</ref> IAP has also advanced [[science diplomacy]] by bringing regional networks together to address global problems.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hassan|first1=Mohamed|date=10 March 2015|title=Academies of Science as Key Instruments of Science Diplomacy|url=http://www.sciencediplomacy.org/perspective/2015/academies-science-key-instruments-science-diplomacy|journal=[[Science & Diplomacy]]|volume=4|issue=1}}</ref>\n\n== Governance ==\nThe highest decisive body of IAP is the [[General assembly|General Assembly]], which meets every third year, and where each member organization has one vote on organizational decisions. At these meetings, member academies elect new leadership, approve new members, report on organizational activities over the last triennial period, and approve a [[Strategic planning|strategic plan]] for the next three years.\n\nIn between the meetings, the work is directed by three executive committees, one for each pillar of the Partnership (or in the case of IAP Policy, a board), supported by a [[Secretariat (administrative office)|secretariat]] from a host academy. Each executive committee/board convenes annually, with two [[Chairperson|co-chairs]] presiding. One of the co-chairs shall be nominated by an academy in a [[Developing country|low or middle income country (LMIC)]]; the other shall be nominated by a [[Developed country|high income country (HIC)]]. Similar rules of diversity in economic development hold for the executive committee member academies in order to represent a global view.<ref>{{cite news|last=Alberts|first=Bruce|url=http://news.scotsman.com/scitech/Independent-research-needs-to-be.3975352.jp|title=Independent research needs to be shared to benefit all of us|date=2008-04-12|work=[[The Scotsman]]|accessdate=2008-05-11|publisher=[[Johnston Press]]}}</ref> The number of member academies composing the executive committee varies: 11 member academies in IAP for Science, 9 member academies in IAP for Health, and 15 member academies in IAP for Policy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.interacademies.org/38723/Governance|title=IAP Governance|url-status=live|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nA Steering Committee composed of the six executive committee/board co-chairs guides the InterAcademy Partnership. From these six Steering Committee members, two are selected to act as co-Presidents. The current co-Presidents are Volker ter Meulen (Germany) and Depei Liu (China). A Board includes the Steering Committee along with one representative from each of four regional networks of academies: in [[African Academy of Sciences|Africa]], the [[InterAmerican Network of Academies of Sciences|Americas]], the Asia/Pacific region, and Europe, for a total of ten representatives.\n\n== Current and former co-chairs ==\n*[[Cherry A. Murray]], US. IAP-Science, 2019\u2013present\n*Masresha Fetene, Ethiopia. IAP-Policy, 2019\u2013present\n*[[Margaret Hamburg]], US. IAP-Health, 2016\u2013present\n*[[Krishna Lal Chadha|Krishan Lal]], India. IAP-Science, 2016\u2013present\n*Liu Depei, China. IAP-Health, 2016\u2013present\n*[[Richard Catlow]], UK. IAP-Policy, 2016\u2013present\n*Volker ter Meulen, Germany. IAP-Science, 2013-2019\n*[[Detlev Ganten]], Germany. IAP-Health, 2013-2019\n*[[Daya Reddy]], South Africa. IAP-Policy, 2012-2019\n*[[Mohamed H.A. Hassan|Mohammed H.A. Hassan]], Sudan. IAP-Science, 2010-2016\n*Lai Meng Loi, Malaysia. IAP-Health, 2010-2016\n*[[Jo Ivey Boufford]], US. IAP-Health, 2010-2013\n*[[Robbert Dijkgraaf]], Netherlands. IAP-Policy, 2008-2016\n*[[Lu Yongxiang (engineer)|Lu Yongxiang]], China. IAP-Policy, 2008-2012\n*[[Howard Alper]], Canada. IAP-Science, 2007-2013\n*Anthony Mbewu, South Africa. IAP-Health, 2007-2010\n*[[Chen Zhu]], China. IAP-Science, 2003-2010\n*Guy de Th\u00e9, France. IAP-Health, 2000-2010\n*[[Bruce Alberts]], US. IAP-Policy, 2000-2008\n*[[Goverdhan Mehta]], India. IAP-Policy, 2000-2008\n*[[Yves Qu\u00e9r\u00e9]], France. IAP-Science, 2000-2007\n*David Challoner, US. IAP-Health, 2000-2006\n*[[Eduardo Krieger]], Brazil. IAP-Science, until 2003\n\n== IAP reports ==\nIAP publishes reports and recommendations that utilize the expertise of member academies to address issues of interest to the global [[Scientific community|scientific]] and policy communities. IAP reports are not endorsed by academy members, but instead must have the [[Consensus decision-making|consensus]] of an expert committee and undergo a rigorous [[Scholarly peer review|peer review]] process. Examples of IAP reports include:\n\n# [https://www.interacademies.org/56874/SEM_for_Africa Harnessing science, engineering, and medicine (SEM) to address Africa's challenges: The role of African national academies], 2019\n# [https://www.interacademies.org/50429/SDGs_Report Improving scientific input to global policymaking with a focus on the UN Sustainable Development Goals], 2019\n# [https://www.interacademies.org/48898/Opportunities-for-future-research-and-innovation-on-food-and-nutrition-security-and-agriculture-The-InterAcademy-Partnerships-global-perspective Opportunities for future research and innovation on food and nutrition security and agriculture: The InterAcademy Partnership's global perspective], 2018\n# [https://www.interacademies.org/33367/Enhancing-the-Capacity-of-African-Science-Academies Enhancing the capacity of African science academies], 2015\n# [https://www.interacademies.org/33362/Responsible-Conduct-in-the-Global-Research-Enterprise Responsible conduct in the global research enterprise], 2012\n# [https://www.interacademies.org/33348/Lighting-the-Way-Toward-a-Sustainable-Energy-Future Lighting the way: Toward a sustainable energy future], 2007\n# [https://www.interacademies.org/33366/Realizing-the-Promise-and-Potential-of-African-Agriculture Realizing the promise and potential of African agriculture], 2004\n\n== IAP statements ==\nIAP also promotes its goals through \"statements on issues of fundamental importance to humanity.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.interacademies.org/10878/Statements|title=Statements|website=InterAcademy Partnership|url-status=live|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> Statements present the combined [[Consensus decision-making|consensus]] of the world's academies to provide independent, [[Evidence-based practice|evidence-based]] advice and recommendations to policymakers in governments, international organizations, or academies themselves. Often an IAP statement can be used to [[Globalization|globalise]] an issue on which a [[national academy]] or regional network of academies has already done a significant amount of work.\n\nAn IAP statement is developed following a specific procedure and released only when the [[majority]] of IAP member academies have endorsed its contents. [https://web.archive.org/web/20090124224136/http://interacademies.net/Object.File/Master/8/487/IAP%20StatementsPRINT-1.pdf], p.&nbsp;4. Thus, the statements are intended to represent the consensus of the [[scientific community]] rather than statements of IAP as an organisation in itself.\n\nAs of 2020, IAP has issued twenty-one statements, as listed below.\n\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/53599/IAP-Health-A-call-for-action-to-declare-trauma-as-a-disease IAP call for action to declare trauma as a disease], 2019. Signed by 46 of IAP for Health's 78 member academies.\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/45731/IAP-for-Health-A-call-for-action-to-tackle-the-growing-burden-of-dementia IAP call for action to tackle the growing burden of dementia], 2018. Signed by 53 of IAP for Health's 78 member academies.\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/38806/IAP-Statement-on-Climate-Change-and-Education IAP statement on climate change and education], 2017. Signed by the majority of IAP for Science's 113 member academies.\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/36499/IAP-Statement-on-Science-and-Technology-for-Disaster-Risk-Reduction IAP statement on science and technology for disaster risk reduction], 2017. Signed by the majority of IAP for Science's 113 member academies.\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/39535/Improving-the-reproducibility-of-biomedical-research-a-call-for-action IAP call for action to improve the reproducibility of biomedical research], 2016. Signed by 46 members.\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/48835/IAP-for-Health-statement-Call-for-Action-to-Strengthen-Health-Research-Capacity-in-Low-and-Middle-Income-Countries IAMP call for action to strengthen health research capacity], 2013. Signed by 42 members.\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/19191/IAP-Statement-on-Population-and-Consumption IAP statement on population and consumption], 2012. Signed by 105 members.\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/14745/IAMP-Statement-on-the-Health-CoBenefits-of-Policies-to-Tackle-Climate-Change IAMP statement on the health co-benefits of policies to tackle climate change], 2010. Signed by 43 members.\n#[http://www.interacademies.net/10878/13954.aspx IAP statement on tropical forests and climate change], 2009. Signed by 54 members.\n#[http://www.interacademies.net/File.aspx?id=9075 IAP statement on ocean acidification], 2009. Signed by 70 members. The academies state that [[Ocean acidification|ocean water acidity has risen]] due to increased [[carbon dioxide]] (CO<sub>2</sub>) caused by human activities, and that it probably will rise further with severe effects on [[marine ecosystem]]s if the emission of CO<sub>2</sub> does not decrease considerably. They urge the issue be recognized among the problems addressed by the [[United Nations Climate Change Conference 2009]] in [[Copenhagen]].\n#IAP statement on the teaching of [[evolution]], 2006. [https://www.interacademies.org/13901/IAP-Statement-on-the-Teaching-of-Evolution Signed by 70 members].\n#IAP statement on [[biosecurity]], 2005, [https://www.interacademies.org/13912/IAP-Statement-on-Biosecurity signed by 71 members].\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/13916/IAP-Statement-on-Access-to-Scientific-Information IAP statement on access to scientific information], 2003, signed by 68 members.\n#IAP statement on science and the [[Media (communication)|media]], 2003, [https://www.interacademies.org/13921/IAP-Statement-on-Science-and-the-Media signed by 68 members].\n#IAP statement on scientific [[capacity building]], 2003, [https://www.interacademies.org/13925/IAP-Statement-on-Scientific-Capacity-Building signed by 68 members].\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/13923/IAP-Statement-on-Science-Education IAP statement on science education of children], 2003, signed by 68 members.\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/13928/IAP-Statement-on-Mother-and-Child-Health IAP statement on health of mother and child in developing countries], 2003, signed by 67 members.\n#IAP statement on [[human cloning]], 2003, [https://www.interacademies.org/13930/IAP-Statement-Calling-for-a-Ban-on-Human-Reproductive-Cloning signed by 67 members]. The academies support \"a worldwide ban on the reproductive cloning of human beings\", but at the same time call for \"cloning to obtain [[embryonic stem cells]] for both research and therapeutic purposes to be excluded from this ban\".\n#IAP statement on transition to [[sustainability]], 2000, [https://www.interacademies.org/13933/IAP-Statement-on-Transition-to-Sustainability signed by 63 members].\n#[https://www.interacademies.org/13937/IAP-Statement-on-Urban-Development IAP statement on science and technology and the future of cities], 1996, signed by 71 members. The academies note that there is an ongoing rapid worldwide [[urbanisation|urbanization]]. They state that this in itself is not necessarily a bad development, but that it may have rather negative effects, if appropriate measures are not taken in order to ensure the new city dwellers e.g. access to water and adequate housing. Therefore, active city planning is necessary, and so is further research on urbanization.\n#[[IAP statement on population growth]], proposed 1993, ratified 1994, [https://www.interacademies.org/13940/IAP-Statement-on-Population-Growth signed by 58 members]. The academies state that \"the world is undergoing an unprecedented population expansion\", and that it is necessary to stop it. They noted that the amount of food produced (both on land and sea) per person was decreasing, and stated that many [[environmental problems]] were aggravated by the [[population expansion]]. The academies state that we must reach \"zero population growth within the lifetime of our children\". They enumerate means which should be taken to achieve this, and also to counteract the effects of the population growth on environment and food production, inter alia. This includes furthering equal opportunities for women, easy access to cheap and safe [[contraceptives]], broad primary health care, governmental policies recognizing longer-term environmental responsibilities, and increased research on cultural, religious, and other factors, which \"affect reproductive behavior\".\n\n=== Role in reviewing the IPCC process ===\n{{further|Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change#InterAcademy Council review}}\n\nIn 2010, the council board recommended changes in the [[IPCC]], such as having an executive committee with \"individuals from outside the IPCC or even outside the [[climate science]] community.\"<ref>[http://reviewipcc.interacademycouncil.net/ReportNewsRelease.html InterAcademy Council Report Recommends Fundamental Reform of IPCC Management Structure]</ref>\nMajor changes from then within the IPCC approach include a stronger focus on the treatment of uncertainty (since the IAC 2010 IPCC review) and the involvement of risk management deliberations (based on fundamental conclusions in the AR4 Synthesis Report).<ref name=ess>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1007/s10584-011-0176-8|title = Evaluation, characterization, and communication of uncertainty by the intergovernmental panel on climate change\u2014an introductory essay|journal = Climatic Change|volume = 108|issue = 4|pages = 629\u2013639|year = 2011|last1 = Yohe|first1 = Gary|last2 = Oppenheimer|first2 = Michael|doi-access = free}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[International Council for Science]]\n*[[InterAmerican Network of Academies of Sciences]]\n*[[Network of African Science Academies]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.interacademies.org/ InterAcademy Partnership]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Interacademy Panel on International Issues}}\n[[Category:InterAcademy Panel]]\n[[Category:International science academies cooperation organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/InterAcademy_Partnership"}
{"title_page": "La Gazette d'Isra\u00ebl", "text_new": "'''La Gazette d'Isra\u00ebl''' is a [[tunisian]] francophonic newspaper for the jewish commmunity founded in october 1938 by E.Ganem in [[Tunis]]. Its editor-in-chief was Henri Emmanuel<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/?url=https://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopedia-of-jews-in-the-islamic-world/la-gazette-disrael-tunis-SIM_0013230|title=Wikiwix's cache|website=archive.wikiwix.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>.\n== History ==\n=== Context ===\nThe weekly newspaper was created painly to create an opposition political force against the conservative and nationalist journals ''[[Le R\u00e9veil juif|Le R\u00e9veil Juif]]'' and ''[[Kadima]]'' that dominated the jewish media sphere by that time.\n\nIt is considered as an organ of the revisionnist zionsit system in Tunisia that until the end of World War II was not really interested in the question of the [[Alya]] and the holy land, while focusing manly on local issues such as the learing of hebrew within the tunisian community, the socio-economic situation of the jewish district in the medina of Tunis, or the rights of the jewish people as tunisian citizens<ref>{{Cite book|last=Allagui|first=Abdelkarim|title=Muslims and jews of Tunisia:From the origins till our days|publisher=Tallandier/Aladin|year=2016|isbn=979-10-210-2077-1|location=Paris|pages=p. 98}}</ref>. \n\nThe last issue of La Gazette d'Isra\u00ebl was published in 1951<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lccn.loc.gov/sv91044266|title=La Gazette d\u2019Isra\u00ebl|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\n=== Directors ===\nThe journal was managed by:\n* David Boccara\n* Raymond Cohen\n* Victor Haouzi\n* Andr\u00e9 Scemmama<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== La Gazette d'Isra\u00ebl in numbers ==\nDepending on the issue, the journal's number of pages varied between 2 and 4.\nBetween 1938 (year of creation) and july 1939, 2000 copies were printed. Between december 1945 and september 1951, 15000 copies were published.\n== See also ==\n*''[[L'\u00e9galit\u00e9 (Newspaper)|L'\u00e9galit\u00e9]]''\n*''[[La Justice (Tunisian newspaper)|La Justice]]''\n*''[[Le R\u00e9veil juif|Le R\u00e9veil Juif]]''\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n", "text_old": "'''La Gazette d'Isra\u00ebl''' is a [[tunisian]] francophonic newspaper for the jewish commmunity founded in october 1938 by E.Ganem in [[Tunis]]. Its editor-in-chief was Henri Emmanuel<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/?url=https://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopedia-of-jews-in-the-islamic-world/la-gazette-disrael-tunis-SIM_0013230|title=Wikiwix's cache|website=archive.wikiwix.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>.\n== History ==\n=== Context ===\nThe weekly newspaper was created painly to create an opposition political force against the conservative and nationalist journals ''[[Le R\u00e9veil juif|Le R\u00e9veil Juif]]'' and ''[[Kadima]]'' that dominated the jewish media sphere by that time.\n\nIt is considered as an organ of the revisionnist zionsit system in Tunisia that until the end of World War II was not really interested in the question of the [[Alya]] and the holy land, while focusing manly on local issues such as the learing of hebrew within the tunisian community, the socio-economic situation of the jewish district in the medina of Tunis, or the rights of the jewish people as tunisian citizens<ref>{{Cite book|last=Allagui|first=Abdelkarim|title=Muslims and jews of Tunisia:From the origins till our days|publisher=Tallandier/Aladin|year=2016|isbn=979-10-210-2077-1|location=Paris|pages=p. 98}}</ref>. \n\nThe last issue of La Gazette d'Isra\u00ebl was published in 1999<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lccn.loc.gov/sv91044266|title=La Gazette d\u2019Isra\u00ebl|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n=== Directors ===\nThe journal was managed by:\n* David Boccara\n* Raymond Cohen\n* Victor Haouzi\n* Andr\u00e9 Scemmama<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== La Gazette d'Isra\u00ebl in numbers ==\nDepending on the issue, the journal's number of pages varied between 2 and 4.\nBetween 1938 (year of creation) and july 1939, 2000 copies were printed. Between december 1945 and september 1951, 15000 copies were published.\n== See also ==\n*''[[L'\u00e9galit\u00e9 (Newspaper)|L'\u00e9galit\u00e9]]''\n*''[[La Justice (Tunisian newspaper)|La Justice]]''\n*''[[Le R\u00e9veil juif|Le R\u00e9veil Juif]]''\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n", "name_user": "Moumou82", "label": "safe", "comment": "according to the source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_Gazette_d%27Isra%C3%ABl"}
